Usually, most of the dreams would involve being in the first person as a human in a war.
It was never explicitly mentioned in my dreams, but it was heavily implied that the conflict was based on the Chechen Wars, with a twist.
The big twist was Anthros, and how very similarly to another story in the masterbin, there is a division between humans and anthros.
However, the difference is that humans and anthros are participating on both sides of the conflict, but on some sides more than others though.
Originally, I was put into the perspective of a human commander of a small detachment of a special unit of Interior Ministry troops, assigned to do investigations on all the missing supplies and equipment off of military bases in the area of operation(s).
Most of it consisted of going around to surrounding villages and towns to "talk to" some of the locals.
While en route to one of these villages, we get ambushed.
Long story short, we dispatch the ambushers and head deeper into the village to find clues. There, we find a family of anthro wolves, consisting of an elderly wolf and his female mate, two granddaughters, one around the age of 5-6, while the other is around her mid 20's.
The one in her mid 20's was extremely hostile and apparently spiteful of our presence, while her grandparents were understanding and patient.
Throughout the discussion, she was constantly interjecting (angrily, might I add), and when told to be silent, she would growl or snarl softly.
After the discussion, I thanked the family for their cooperation and offered a small pack of candies to the younger wolf.
She accepted, much to her sister's dismay, and we disembarked.
On the way back, I asked my second-in-command to give me an investigative report on the family, the older daughter seemed suspicious.
After that, some more fluff about the world and shit, but on a second run to the village we encountered more resistance.
After the ambush, we found a wounded anthro wolf.

>>23257442
The relationship is just an easy locus for tension in stories. I suppose I should have said that stories without conflict or tension - whether it arises between the romantic leads or through the setting itself - are uninteresting, trite. For example, a post-apocalyptic setting presents so many challenges that, if anything, the romantic leads would probably have a strong cooperative relationship, even before any romance is established. In any case, I think I've clarified well enough. The ooey-gooey stories built around unhindered romance and smut are meh. They fail to arouse interest in the leads or any care for their well-being. Character psychology is extremely important, and if I don't care enough to want to know a principal, I'm not gonna wanna read much of his/her story. On the other hand, it's really noticeable when an author wants to make a couple interesting but is struggling to create tension; the setting and progression will feel very forced. I've noticed that trend in stories with medieval fantasy settings the most, whereas the former is mostly observable in stories with modern urban/suburban settings.
